Friday, 7 Jan 2022 10:01 AM;liualg;*From:* Liu, Alexander (NIH/NCI) [C] <alexander.liu@nih.gov>
 *Date:* Friday, January 7, 2022 at 10:00 AM
 *To:* brigid.m.wilson@gmail.com <brigid.m.wilson@gmail.com>
 *Cc:* SeroNetCoordinatingCenter <SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov>, Freund, Elaine (NIH/NCI) [C] <elaine.freund@nih.gov>, christopher.king@case.edu <christopher.king@case.edu>
 *Subject:* Published SeroNet Data Sets- next steps

Dear Dr. Wilson,

 

Thank you for serving as the data point of contact (POC) for the publications below. As a next step+,+ we are requesting the data set(s) that support the research findings of this publication and an Institutional Certification (attached) for release of the human subjects data. 

 

Please provide the requested data by COB 01/14/2022. The Institutional Certifications for both papers will be needed prior to public release of the data. I have attached requirements for the Institutional Certification as well as its associated form.

 
|Award|PMID|Title|Journal|
|CA260539
 |33993265 
 |  Reduced BNT162b2 Messenger RNA Vaccine Response in Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus 2 (SARS-CoV-2)-Naive Nursing Home Residents|Clin Infect Dis
 |
|CA260539
 |34652783
 |Does a lack of vaccine side effects correlate with reduced BNT162b2 mRNA vaccine response among healthcare workers and nursing home residents?|Aging Clin Exp Res
 |

 

The Data Coordinating Center will work iteratively with you to prepare the data set(s) for submission into ImmPort, the SeroNet public (open access) data repository. We can advise you on appropriate additional repositories for data that does not fit into the ImmPort model (e.g. genomic data, in silico models). NIH Box is being used to accept data submissions to the SeroNet Coordinating Center. Below are the steps for setting up and using Box for your data submission:
 * You will receive an email invitation inviting you to collaborate on NIH Box.   
 * The invitation will indicate a folder named with the PMID number indicated above. 


 * When you accept the invitation, you will be asked to create an account to access the data submission folder on NIH Box.  
 *  If you have any issues creating your account email: [CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov|mailto:CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov] 


 * Once the account is created you will be able to upload the data file(s) supporting this publication. 
 * Please upload the data files to the submitted_data folder. 
 * If you have very large data files (greater than 10 Mb) let’s schedule a call or discuss by email before you upload.   

 

Our curators will complete the two templates that are key for finding your publication in a search of SeroNet papers. They will review the submitted data and reach out to you with any questions they have. Where appropriate they will identify additional ImmPort templates for you to populate in preparation of the data for submission to a public data repository. They are also available to answer questions you may have.   If the data has already been submitted to a public data repository, we ask that you still sign up for the NIH Box account. We will still need your documenting that information for the SeroNet article registry (in ImmPort) and will use NIH Box in our workflow.   

 

As you prepare your submission be sure to:
 * Include ONLY de-identified data (do not include 18 excluded datatypes such as dates except year, geographic subdivisions smaller than state, or other PHI) unless sharing is approved by your IRB/ expert determination was used to confirm data is de-identified.
 * Include a brief description of the column names
 * Include any applicable units
 * Define the codes for any coded values (e.g., 0 = yes, 1= no) 
 * Define any blank values (e.g., not collected, not applicable, not tested, no data etc.)

 

If you have any questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to reach out directly to  [SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov|mailto:SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov].

 

 

Best,

Alex

 

 

_Alexander Liu (Contractor)_

SeroNet Curator

 

Essential Software Inc. (ESI)

Center for Biomedical Informatics and Information Technology (CBIIT)

9609 Medical Center Drive,

Rockville, MD 20850

Email: liualg@nih.gov

Sorry for the long Hiatus on our end. There have been some updates and revisions to our workflow.

Alongside this, the SeroNet is now requiring all manuscripts that use human subject data to include an Institutional Certification (attached) for release of the human subjects’ data. I have attached details on the requirements as well as the certification.  

 

Best,

Alex

Tuesday, 11 Jan 2022 09:28 AM;liualg;*From:* Liu, Alexander (NIH/NCI) [C] <alexander.liu@nih.gov>
 *Date:* Friday, January 7, 2022 at 11:20 AM
 *To:* Benjamin Pinsky <bpinsky@STANFORD.EDU>
 *Cc:* Scott Boyd <sboyd1@stanford.edu>, SeroNetCoordinatingCenter <SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov>, Bastola, Mrigendra (NIH/NCI) [C] <mrigendra.bastola@nih.gov>, Freund, Elaine (NIH/NCI) [C] <elaine.freund@nih.gov>
 *Subject:* Re: Published SeroNet Data Sets- next steps

Dear Dr.Pinksy,  

 

This is just a reminder and update from the SeroNet Coordinating Center.

 

Thank you for serving as the data point of contact (POC) for the publication below. As a next step+,+ we are requesting the data set(s) that support the research findings of this publication and an Institutional Certification (attached) for release of the human subjects data.  

  

Please provide the requested data by *COB 01/14/2022*. The Institutional Certification will be needed prior to public release of the data.  

  
|Award  |PMID  |Title  |Journal  |
|CA260517|33915337|Increased viral variants in children and young adults with impaired humoral immunity and persistent SARS-CoV-2 infection: A consecutive case series.
 |EBioMedicine
 |
|CA260517|33720347|Case-Control Study of Individuals with Discrepant Nucleocapsid and Spike Protein SARS-CoV-2 IgG Results
 | Clinical Chemistry
 |
|CA260517|33932848 | Evaluation of SARS-CoV-2 total antibody detection via a lateral flow nanoparticle fluorescence immunoassay.|  Journal of clinical virology|

  

The Data Coordinating Center will work iteratively with you to prepare the data set(s) for submission into ImmPort, the SeroNet public (open access) data repository. We can advise you on appropriate additional repositories for data that does not fit into the ImmPort model (e.g. genomic data, in silico models). NIH Box is being used to accept data submissions to the SeroNet Coordinating Center. Below are the steps for setting up and using Box for your data submission:   

   
 * You will receive an email invitation inviting you to collaborate on NIH Box.     
 * The invitation will indicate a folder named with the PMID number indicated above.   
 * When you accept the invitation, you will be able to to access the data submission folder on NIH Box, and to upload the data file(s) supporting this publication.   
 * Please upload the data files to the *submitted_data*    
 *  If you have any issues accessing your account, please contact NIH Box support at email: [CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov|mailto:CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov%22%20\t%20%22_blank]   
 *  If you have very large data files (greater than 10 Mb) let’s schedule a call or discuss by email before you upload.     

   

Our curators will complete the two templates that are key for finding your publication in a search of SeroNet papers. They will review the submitted data and reach out to you with any questions they have. Where appropriate they will identify additional ImmPort templates for you to populate in preparation of the data for submission to a public data repository. They are also available to answer any questions you may have. If the data has already been submitted to a public data repository, we ask that you still use the NIH Box account. We will still need your assistance documenting that information for the SeroNet article registry (in ImmPort) and will use NIH Box in our workflow.    

  

As you prepare your submission be sure to: 
 * Include ONLY de-identified data (do not include 18 excluded datatypes such as dates except year, geographic subdivisions smaller than state, or other PHI) unless sharing is approved by your IRB/ expert determination was used to confirm data is de-identified. 
 * Include a brief description of the column names 
 * Include any applicable units 
 * Define the codes for any coded values (e.g., 0 = yes, 1= no)   
 * Define any blank values (e.g., not collected, not applicable, not tested, no data etc.) 

 

 

If you have any questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to reach out directly to me or  [SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov|mailto:SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov].   

  

Best Regards,  

Alex

 

 

_Alexander Liu (Contractor)_

SeroNet Curator

 

Essential Software Inc. (ESI)

Center for Biomedical Informatics and Information Technology (CBIIT)

9609 Medical Center Drive,

Rockville, MD 20850

Email: liualg@nih.gov

Tuesday, 11 Jan 2022 09:28 AM;liualg;*From:* Liu, Alexander (NIH/NCI) [C] <alexander.liu@nih.gov>
 *Date:* Friday, January 7, 2022 at 11:20 AM
 *To:* Benjamin Pinsky <bpinsky@STANFORD.EDU>
 *Cc:* Scott Boyd <sboyd1@stanford.edu>, SeroNetCoordinatingCenter <SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov>, Bastola, Mrigendra (NIH/NCI) [C] <mrigendra.bastola@nih.gov>, Freund, Elaine (NIH/NCI) [C] <elaine.freund@nih.gov>
 *Subject:* Re: Published SeroNet Data Sets- next steps

Dear Dr.Pinksy,  

 

This is just a reminder and update from the SeroNet Coordinating Center.

 

Thank you for serving as the data point of contact (POC) for the publication below. As a next step+,+ we are requesting the data set(s) that support the research findings of this publication and an Institutional Certification (attached) for release of the human subjects data.  

  

Please provide the requested data by *COB 01/14/2022*. The Institutional Certification will be needed prior to public release of the data.  

  
|Award  |PMID  |Title  |Journal  |
|CA260517|33915337|Increased viral variants in children and young adults with impaired humoral immunity and persistent SARS-CoV-2 infection: A consecutive case series.
 |EBioMedicine
 |
|CA260517|33720347|Case-Control Study of Individuals with Discrepant Nucleocapsid and Spike Protein SARS-CoV-2 IgG Results
 | Clinical Chemistry
 |
|CA260517|33932848 | Evaluation of SARS-CoV-2 total antibody detection via a lateral flow nanoparticle fluorescence immunoassay.|  Journal of clinical virology|

  

The Data Coordinating Center will work iteratively with you to prepare the data set(s) for submission into ImmPort, the SeroNet public (open access) data repository. We can advise you on appropriate additional repositories for data that does not fit into the ImmPort model (e.g. genomic data, in silico models). NIH Box is being used to accept data submissions to the SeroNet Coordinating Center. Below are the steps for setting up and using Box for your data submission:   

   
 * You will receive an email invitation inviting you to collaborate on NIH Box.     
 * The invitation will indicate a folder named with the PMID number indicated above.   
 * When you accept the invitation, you will be able to to access the data submission folder on NIH Box, and to upload the data file(s) supporting this publication.   
 * Please upload the data files to the *submitted_data*    
 *  If you have any issues accessing your account, please contact NIH Box support at email: [CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov|mailto:CITBoxSupport@mail.nih.gov%22%20\t%20%22_blank]   
 *  If you have very large data files (greater than 10 Mb) let’s schedule a call or discuss by email before you upload.     

   

Our curators will complete the two templates that are key for finding your publication in a search of SeroNet papers. They will review the submitted data and reach out to you with any questions they have. Where appropriate they will identify additional ImmPort templates for you to populate in preparation of the data for submission to a public data repository. They are also available to answer any questions you may have. If the data has already been submitted to a public data repository, we ask that you still use the NIH Box account. We will still need your assistance documenting that information for the SeroNet article registry (in ImmPort) and will use NIH Box in our workflow.    

  

As you prepare your submission be sure to: 
 * Include ONLY de-identified data (do not include 18 excluded datatypes such as dates except year, geographic subdivisions smaller than state, or other PHI) unless sharing is approved by your IRB/ expert determination was used to confirm data is de-identified. 
 * Include a brief description of the column names 
 * Include any applicable units 
 * Define the codes for any coded values (e.g., 0 = yes, 1= no)   
 * Define any blank values (e.g., not collected, not applicable, not tested, no data etc.) 

 

 

If you have any questions or concerns, please do not hesitate to reach out directly to me or  [SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov|mailto:SeroNetCoordinatingCenter@nih.gov].   

  

Best Regards,  

Alex

 

 

_Alexander Liu (Contractor)_

SeroNet Curator

 

Essential Software Inc. (ESI)

Center for Biomedical Informatics and Information Technology (CBIIT)

9609 Medical Center Drive,

Rockville, MD 20850

Email: liualg@nih.gov

Hi,

I have had a few e-mail exchanges with Dr. Hays re: the data for PMID 34083451 “Estimating epidemiologic dynamics from cross-sectional viral load distributions.” He is not the PI on the grant (not SeroNet) that funded getting the original data. This is repurposed data, but he said the original IRB specifically allows for dates to be used. He is currently abroad so we have set an appointment in 2 weeks for follow up.  I recommend keeping the data in Box for now, but let’s not touch it in anyway until we have some resolution.

Thanks,

Elaine
